00:07:24.480 --> 00:07:26.254
was an accordion player.

00:07:26.254 --> 00:07:28.670
And he always wanted to play
the bandoneon, the instrument

00:07:28.670 --> 00:07:30.430
I'm holding right now.

00:07:30.430 --> 00:07:32.820
And it's a very
particular instrument

00:07:32.820 --> 00:07:36.190
because every button plays
two notes, one note when

00:07:36.190 --> 00:07:37.434
I open the bellows.

00:07:37.434 --> 00:07:39.600
And the same button, when
I close, change the pitch.

00:07:43.270 --> 00:07:45.340
And the interval is
always different.

00:07:45.340 --> 00:07:47.520
And in this hand, I
have the lower register.

00:07:47.520 --> 00:07:48.810
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:07:48.810 --> 00:07:49.920
You have a C opening.

00:07:49.920 --> 00:07:54.120
And when I close,
it becomes an F.

00:07:54.120 --> 00:07:57.261
And the interval is
always different again.

00:07:57.261 --> 00:07:59.010
So we have to practice
four keyboards, two

00:07:59.010 --> 00:08:00.801
keyboards opening and
two keywords closing.

00:08:00.801 --> 00:08:03.576
And so that's why my grandfather
choose the accordion.

00:08:03.576 --> 00:08:04.075
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:04.574 --> 00:08:06.380
And so I wrote
this piece for him.

00:08:06.380 --> 00:08:09.380
It's called "Taranguino."

